%S A396454 1,7,19,21,73,79,91,93,259,261,273,279,331,333,345,351,1057,1063,1075,
%T A396454 1077,1129,1135,1147,1149,1315,1317,1329,1335,1387,1389,1401,1407,
%U A396454 4105,4111,4123,4125,4161,4167,4179,4181,4363,4365,4377,4383,4419,4421,4433,4439
%N A396454 Possible values of (A000695(k) XOR k) + 1, in ascending order.
%C A396454 Alternatively, possible values of Q(2) where Q(x) = (P(x))^2+P(x)+1 over GF(2) and P(x) is in GF(2)[X].
%C A396454 a(n) is always odd.
%C A396454 For n >= 1, there are 2^(n-1) elements of this sequence between 4^n and 2*4^n, and no elements between 2*4^n and 4^(n+1).
%C A396454 There are infinitely many positive integers which are both in this sequence and A014580: 2^(2*3^k)+2^(3^k)+1 is a member of both sequences for k >= 0.
%e A396454 A000695(10) = 68, 68 XOR 10 = 78, so 79 is in the sequence.
%e A396454 Let P(x) = x^2+x. Then Q(x) = (P(x))^2+P(x)+1 = x^4+x+1 (over GF(2)), and 2^4+2+1 = 19, so 19 is in the sequence.
%Y A396454 Cf. A000695, A014580.
%K A396454 nonn
%O A396454 1,2
%A A396454 _Ari Wachtel_, May 26 2026
